<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Secretary of State to the
                            Embassy in Nicaragua</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1947v08</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d719</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">719</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1947-01-22T15:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1947-01-22T15:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-01-22T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-01-22T15:00:00-05:00" n="719" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/1–2047: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Nicaragua</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-01-22T15:00:00-05:00">January 22, 1947—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>14. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">Urtel</gloss> 25 Jan 20.<note n="5" xml:id="d719fn1">Not printed; Ambassador Warren reported that he had
                        conveyed orally to President Somoza the substance of Department’s telegram
                        12 of January 18, and the latter had asked that Ambassador Warren let
                        General Chamorro and others know of his request to the Department and its
                        refusal (817.00/1–2047).</note> Were Embassy to comply with President
                    Somoza’s request, it would be acting as intermediary between him and opposition,
                    a procedure which Dept has considered undesirable. No objection is perceived,
                    however, to your confirming facts if inquiry is made by opposition leaders.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
